aking it an explicit lifecycle event allows real-time incremental tracking. The event type clearly distinguishes \"file was modified\" from all other lifecycle phases.\n\n- **Invariant Enforcement**: 6/10\n  No enforcement that `FileEdit` events must have a non-empty `FilePath`. The dispatcher in `handleLifecycleFileEdit` handles this gracefully (returns nil), but the type itself allows construction of `FileEdit` events with empty `FilePath`. This is a pragmatic tradeoff -- see Concerns below.\n\n### Strengths\n- Clean extension of the existing enum pattern\n- iota ordering is backward-compatible (new constant appended at the end)\n- String() method and dispatcher are both updated in lockstep\n\n### Concerns\n- The `Event` struct is a flat \"god struct\" with fields that are only relevant for specific event types (`FilePath` for `FileEdit`, `ToolUseID` for subagent events, `Prompt` for `TurnStart`, etc.). This is a pre-existing design issue that this PR does not worsen significantly by adding one more field.\n- There is no compile-time enforcement that a `FileEdit` event has a `FilePath`. A discriminated union or sealed interface would express this more strongly, but that would be a large architectural change inconsistent with the codebase's established patterns.\n\n### Recommended Improvements\nNone for this PR. The flat-struct approach is a conscious tradeoff in this codebase, and adding one more field does not cross a complexity threshold that would justify refactoring the Event type.\n\n---\n\n## Type: `Event.FilePath` (new field)\n\n**File:** `/Users/alex/workspace/cli/.worktrees/3/cmd/entire/cli/agent/event.go`, line 123-126\n\n### Invariants Identified\n- Should be populated only for `FileEdit` events\n- May be absolute or relative; the framework normalizes before persisting\n- Must not contain newline characters (enforced downstream in `AppendFileTouched`)\n\n### Ratings\n- **Encapsulation**: 5/10\n  The field is public and writable by anyone constructing an