cted schema. This avoids coupling the hook input type to any specific tool's input format. The doc comment explains the provenance clearly.\n\n- **Invariant Usefulness**: 8/10\n  This type fills a real need. Previously there was no Gemini type for AfterTool hook payloads containing tool details. The `ToolName` and `ToolInput` fields enable the new file-edit parsing without modifying the existing `sessionInfoRaw` or `agentHookInputRaw` types (which don't carry tool information).\n\n- **Invariant Enforcement**: 5/10\n  No validation that required fields are non-empty. This is consistent with all other `*Raw` types in this package -- they are deserialization targets, and validation happens in the parsing functions that consume them. The `parseFileEdit` method handles empty/missing fields gracefully.\n\n### Strengths\n- Follows the established `*Raw` naming convention for deserialization-only types\n- Package-private visibility\n- `json.RawMessage` for polymorphic tool input is the standard Go approach\n- Clear doc comment connecting it to Gemini CLI's AfterTool hooks\n\n### Concerns\n- None. This is a well-crafted internal DTO.\n\n---\n\n## Type: `fileEditToolInput` (new, two versions)\n\n**Files:**\n- `/Users/alex/workspace/cli/.worktrees/3/cmd/entire/cli/agent/geminicli/lifecycle.go`, lines 185-189\n- `/Users/alex/workspace/cli/.worktrees/3/cmd/entire/cli/agent/claudecode/lifecycle.go`, lines 191-193\n\n### Invariants Identified\n- Claude version: only `FilePath` field (Claude Write/Edit always use `file_path`)\n- Gemini version: three fields (`FilePath`, `Path`, `Filename`) with a priority order\n- The `filePath()` method on the Gemini version encodes the fallback chain\n\n### Ratings\n- **Encapsulation**: 6/10\n  Both are unexported types, correctly scoped to their packages. The Gemini version has a method that encapsulates the priority logic.\n\n- **Invariant Expression**: 7/10\n  The Gemini version's `filePath()` method clearly encodes the fallback chain: `file_path > path > filename`. The doc comment on the struct explains why three fields exist (\"Gemini tools use file_path, path, or filename depending on the tool\"). The Claude version is simpler because Claude consistently uses `file_path`.\n\n- **Invariant Usefulness**: 8/10\n  Both types solve the practical problem of extracting a file path from heterogeneous tool input JSON. The Gemini version handles real-world variance across four different tools.\n\n- **Invariant Enforcement**: 6/10\n  The `filePath()` method returns empty string when all fields are empty, and callers check for this. This is a clean, sufficient design.\n\n### Strengths\n- Appropriate divergence between Claude (simple) and Gemini (fallback chain)\n- The `filePath()` helper method encapsulates the resolution logic\n- Both types are package-private DTOs used only for JSON deserialization\n\n### Concerns\n- **Name collision**: Both packages define a type named `fileEditToolInput`. This is fine because they are in separate packages, but it creates a mild readability concern when reading the diff. Since they have genuinely different structures (one field vs. three), merging them into a shared type in the `agent` package would be wrong -- they model different agent contracts. The name collision is acceptable.\n- The Gemini `filePath()` method uses a value receiver, which is idiomatic for a small struct. No issue here.\n\n### Recommended Improvements\nNone. The two types correctly model their respective agents' contracts and are appropriately scoped.\n\n---\n\n## Type: `PostFileEditInput` (new, integration test)\n\n**File:** `/Users/alex/workspace/cli/.worktrees/3/cmd/entire/cli/integration_test/hooks.go`, lines 409-415\n\n### Invariants Identified\n- Test helper DTO for simulating post-file-edit hooks\n- Fields mirror the Claude Code PostToolUse hook payload structure\n\n### Ratings\n- **Encapsulation**: 6/10\n  Public fields for test construction. Appropriate for a test helper.\n\n- **Invariant Expression**: 6/10\n  Clear, simple struct. No validation needed for a test input type.\n\n- **Invariant Usefulness**: 7/10\n  Necessary to test the file-edit flow end-to-end. Follows the existing pattern of `PostTodoInput` and similar test input types.\n\n- **Invariant Enforcement**: N/A\n  Test infrastructure types do not need enforcement.\n\n### Strengths\n- Consistent with existing `PostTodoInput` pattern\n- Both `HookRunner.SimulatePostFileEdit` and `TestEnv.SimulatePostFileEdit` convenience methods provided\n\n### Concerns\n- None.\n\n---\n\n## Type: `StateStore` (modified) -- new `AppendFileTouched` / `ReadFilesTouched` / `ClearFilesTouched` methods\n\n**File:** `/Users/alex/workspace/cli/.worktrees/3/cmd/entire/cli/session/state.go`, lines 412-502\n\n### Invariants Identified\n1. Session ID must pass `validation.ValidateSessionID` (prevents path traversal)\n2. File paths must not contain `\\n` or `\\r` (prevents line injection in the append-only format)\n3. The `.files` tracking file uses one-path-per-line format with newline delimiters\n4. `ReadFilesTouched` deduplicates and sorts\n5. `ClearFilesTouched` is idempotent (no error on non-existent file)\n6. `Clear()` already uses a glob (`sessionID+\".*\"`) to remove all session files, so `.files` is automatically cleaned up\n\n### Ratings\n- **Encapsulation**: 8/10\n  All file path manipulation is internal. The public API is `AppendFileTouched(ctx, sessionID, filePath)` -- callers don't know about the `.files` file format. The `filesTouchedPath` helper is private. The design is clean.\n\n- **Invariant Expression**: 8/10\n  The line-injection guard (`strings.ContainsAny(filePath, \"\\n\\r\")`) directly protects the file format invariant. Session ID validation prevents path traversal. The deduplicate-on-read contract is clearly documented.\n\n- **Invariant Usefulness**: 9/10\n  These methods solve a critical performance problem: the previous approach required parsing the full transcript at commit time to discover which files were modified. The new append-only tracking file makes this O(1) per tool invocation, with read being O(n) in files touched (which is always small). The design is intentionally lightweight -- no JSON parsing, no file locking, just `O_APPEND` writes.\n\n- **Invariant Enforcement**: 8/10\n  - Session ID validated on every operation (Append, Read, Clear)\n  - Newline injection prevented on write\n  - Directory created with restrictive permissions (0o750)\n  - File created with restrictive permissions (0o600)\n  - Idempotent clear (no error on non-existent)\n  - Existing `Clear()` method already cleans up `.files` via the `sessionID+\".*\"` glob pattern\n\n### Strengths\n- The append-only write / deduplicate-on-read pattern is a smart design for this use case. It avoids any need for file locking even with concurrent tool invocations within the same session.\n- `O_APPEND` is atomic on POSIX for writes smaller than `PIPE_BUF` (4096 bytes), so concurrent appends of file paths will not interleave.\n- The `Clear()` glob already covers `.files` -- no separate cleanup path needed.\n- Thorough test coverage including: deduplication, idempotent clear, session ID validation, newline injection rejection, and cleanup of `.files` alongside `.json` state.\n\n### Concerns\n1. **No file locking for concurrent sessions.** Two concurrent sessions with the same session ID could write to the same `.files` file. However, the CLAUDE.md documentation indicates this is the expected behavior (\"both sessions can proceed -- their checkpoints interleave on the same shadow branch\"). The `O_APPEND` mode ensures atomic appends.\n\n2. **Unbounded file growth within a session.** If an agent edits the same file 10,000 times, the `.files` file grows linearly. Deduplication only happens on read. For most sessions this is negligible, but pathological cases could produce large tracking files. The `clearFilesTracking` calls at condensation/commit time bound the actual lifetime.\n\n3. **`strings.SplitSeq` usage in `ReadFilesTouched`.** This uses Go 1.24's iterator-based split. The project uses Go 1.25.x per CLAUDE.md, so this is fine. Just noting this as a newer API that may surprise readers.\n\n### Recommended Improvements\nNone for this PR. The append-only pattern is the right tradeoff for a hot path (called on every file edit). The unbounded growth concern is mitigated by the clearing at commit time.\n\n---\n\n## Type: `FileModificationTools` (modified, Gemini CLI)\n\n**File:** `/Users/alex/workspace/cli/.worktrees/3/cmd/entire/cli/agent/geminicli/types.go`, lines 98-104\n\n### Invariants Identified\n- Lists all Gemini CLI tool names that modify files\n- Used both for hook installation (AfterTool matchers) and for transcript analysis\n- Must be kept in sync with Gemini CLI's actual tool naming\n\n### Ratings\n- **Encapsulation**: 5/10\n  Public `var` (mutable slice). Any consumer could mutate it at runtime. This is a pre-existing issue -- the slice was exported before this PR.\n\n- **Invariant Expression**: 7/10\n  The associated `Tool*` constants (`ToolWriteFile`, `ToolEditFile`, `ToolSaveFile`, `ToolReplace`) clearly name each tool. The doc comment explains the naming inconsistency between internal and display names.\n\n- **Invariant Usefulness**: 8/10\n  Single source of truth for file-modifying tools, reused across hook installation, transcript analysis, and now hook-based file tracking.\n\n- **Invariant Enforcement**: 4/10\n  Being a mutable exported `var`, it can be modified at runtime. This is low-risk in practice since it is never mutated after initialization, but technically violates immutability principles.\n\n### Concerns\n- The mutable `var` export is a pre-existing pattern across all agents (Claude Code, OpenCode, FactoryAIDroid all export `FileModificationTools` the same way). This PR does not change the pattern.\n\n### Recommended Improvements\nThis is outside the scope of this PR, but converting to a function (`func FileModificationTools() []string`) that returns a copy would prevent mutation. Not urgent.\n\n---\n\n## Cross-cutting Analysis\n\n### Backward Compatibility\n\nThe changes are fully backward-compatible:\n- `EventType.FileEdit` is appended at the end of the iota sequence (value 9), so all existing constants retain their values.\n- `Event.FilePath` is a new optional field with zero value `\"\"`. Existing code that constructs `Event` values will continue to work.\n- The `State.FilesTouched` field in session JSON is unchanged. The new `.files` tracking file is a complementary data source, and `resolveFilesTouched` merges both sources.\n- The `Clear()` method's glob (`sessionID+\".*\"`) already covers the new `.files` extension without code changes.\n\n### Naming Consistency\n\n- `HookNamePostFileEdit = \"post-file-edit\"` is defined identically in both `claudecode` and `geminicli` packages. The comment in `hook_registry.go` (line 83: \"same value for all agents\") correctly notes this. This is a reasonable approach that avoids a shared constant while documenting the coupling.\n- `fileEditToolInput` is defined in both packages with different structures. The name collision is acceptable because the types are package-private and model genuinely different contracts.\n- `PostFileEditInput` in integration tests follows the established `Post*Input` naming convention.\n- `AppendFileTouched` / `ReadFilesTouched` / `ClearFilesTouched` follow a clear CRUD naming pattern on `StateStore`.\n\n### Design Pattern Observations\n\nThe `handleLifecycleFileEdit` handler intentionally swallows all errors (returns `nil` unconditionally), logging them as warnings. This is documented and deliberate: file tracking is an optimization over transcript parsing, not a correctness requirement. If tracking fails, the fallback in `resolveFilesTouched` will still extract file information from the transcript. This layered-fallback design is sound.\n\nThe `resolveFilesTouched` changes in `manual_commit_hooks.go` merge three sources