id>\n<status>completed</status>\n<summary>Agent \"Silent failure analysis\" completed</summary>\n<result>Now I have everything I need for a thorough audit. Let me compile the findings.\n\n---\n\n# Error Handling Audit: `post-file-edit-gemini` PR\n\n## Summary\n\nThis PR introduces a `FileEdit` lifecycle event to track files modified by agents (both Claude Code and Gemini CLI) via per-session `.files` tracking files. It also modifies `resolveFilesTouched` to merge state and tracking file data, and adds `clearFilesTracking` calls during condensation and carry-forward. Overall, the error handling quality is moderate to good -- most errors are logged and the design intent of \"never block the agent\" is clear. However, there are several issues ranging from medium to high severity.\n\n---\n\n## Issue 1: `handleLifecycleFileEdit` silently swallows all errors -- returns nil unconditionally\n\n**Location:** `/Users/alex/workspace/cli/.worktrees/3/cmd/entire/cli/lifecycle.go`, lines 179-219\n\n**Severity:** HIGH\n\n**Issue Description:** The function comment explicitly states \"Returns nil unconditionally; errors are logged but not propagated to avoid blocking the agent.\" While the *intent* is defensible (a file-tracking failure should not block the agent), every error path returns `nil` after only a `Warn`-level log. This means callers (specifically `DispatchLifecycleEvent`) receive no indication that anything went wrong. The design choice to never propagate errors from this handler means:\n\n1. If `paths.WorktreeRoot` consistently fails (e.g., corrupted `.git`), every single file edit will silently fail tracking, and the user will discover at commit time that none of their session's files were tracked -- with no explanation.\n2. If `session.NewStateStore` fails (e.g., permissions issue on `.git/entire-sessions/`), the same silent failure pattern accumulates indefinitely.\n\n**User Impact:** Users will see stale or empty `FilesTouched` data at commit time with no explanation of why file tracking stopped working. The `resolveFilesTouched` function will fall back to transcript extraction (which is slower and less reliable), and the user will never know the tracking mechanism broke.\n\n**Recommendation:** This is a legitimate design decision (don't block the agent), but it should be documented more clearly in the function, and the logging should be at `Error` level for repeated failures, not just `Warn`. At minimum, consider returning the error wrapped in a non-fatal marker so callers can log appropriately. The current approach of `Warn` logging is adequate for individual failures but provides no mechanism to escalate when failures are persistent.\n\n---\n\n## Issue 2: `clearFilesTracking` silently returns on `getStateStore` failure without any logging\n\n**Location:** `/Users/alex/workspace/cli/.worktrees/3/cmd/entire/cli/strategy/manual_commit_hooks.go`, lines 1514-1526\n\n**Severity:** HIGH\n\n**Issue Description:** When `getStateStore` fails, the function silently returns with zero logging:\n\n```go\nfunc (s *ManualCommitStrategy) clearFilesTracking(ctx context.Context, sessionID string) {\n\tstore, storeErr := s.getStateStore(ctx)\n\tif storeErr != nil {\n\t\treturn  // <-- SILENT RETURN, NO LOGGING\n\t}\n\t...\n}\n```\n\nThe `ClearFilesTouched` error path (line 1519-1525) at least logs at `Debug` level, but the `getStateStore` failure is completely silent. This means if the state store cannot be initialized (e.g., not in a git repo, disk permissions), the tracking file will accumulate indefinitely without cleanup, and there will be zero diagnostic evidence.\n\nThis function is called from two critical paths:\n1. After `condenseAndUpdateState` (line 1124) -- tracking data from a completed condensation is not cleaned up\n2. After carry-forward (line 1031) -- stale entries remain in the tracking file\n\n**Hidden Errors:** Disk permission errors, git directory not found, filesystem errors.\n\n**User Impact:** Stale `.files` data accumulates silently. On next `resolveFilesTouched`, old file entries from previous condensations will be merged back in, causing `FilesTouched` to contain files that were already committed. This could cause redundant condensation or incorrect carry-forward calculations.\n\n**Recommendation:** Add at least `Debug`-level logging when `getStateStore` fails, consistent with the `ClearFilesTouched` error path:\n\n```go\nif storeErr != nil {\n    logCtx := logging.WithComponent(ctx, \"checkpoint\")\n    logging.Debug(logCtx, \"clearFilesTracking: could not get state store (non-critical)\",\n        slog.String(\"session_id\", sessionID),\n        slog.String(\"error\", storeErr.Error()),\n    )\n    return\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n## Issue 3: `resolveFilesTouched` downgrades state store and file read errors to Debug-level logging\n\n**Location:** `/Users/alex/workspace/cli/.worktrees/3/cmd/entire/cli/strategy/manual_commit_hooks.go`, lines 1464-1509\n\n**Severity:** MEDIUM\n\n**Issue Description:** When `getStateStore` or `ReadFilesTouched` fails, the function logs at `Debug` level and falls back to transcript extraction. Debug logs are typically not visible in production:\n\n```go\nif store, err := s.getStateStore(ctx); err != nil {\n    logging.Debug(logCtx, \"resolveFilesTouched: could not get state store, falling back to transcript\",\n        ...\n    )\n} else if files, readErr := store.ReadFilesTouched(ctx, state.SessionID); readErr != nil {\n    logging.Debug(logCtx, \"resolveFilesTouched: could not read tracking file, falling back to transcript\",\n        ...\n    )\n}\n```\n\nThis is a fallback chain that silently degrades to a slower, less reliable code path (transcript extraction) without any user-visible indication. The fallback behavior is architecturally reasonable, but the logging severity is too low for production troubleshooting.\n\n**User Impact:** If the tracking file mechanism is broken (permissions, corrupted data), the system silently falls back to transcript