rmat\n    return nil, nil\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n## Issue 5: `AppendFileTouched` does not check `f.Close()` error on write-mode file\n\n**Location:** `/Users/alex/workspace/cli/.worktrees/3/cmd/entire/cli/session/state.go`, lines 434-443\n\n**Severity:** MEDIUM\n\n**Issue Description:** The file is opened with `O_APPEND|O_CREATE|O_WRONLY` and closed via `defer f.Close()`. The `Close()` return value is discarded. On certain filesystems (especially NFS, or when the filesystem is full), `Close()` can be the point where buffered write errors are surfaced. The `fmt.Fprintln` write may succeed in user-space buffers but fail to flush to disk, and the error would only be reported by `Close()`.\n\nThe pattern is:\n```go\nf, err := os.OpenFile(...)\ndefer f.Close()        // <-- error not checked\n_, err = fmt.Fprintln(f, filePath)\nreturn ...\n```\n\n**User Impact:** On filesystem edge cases, a write could appear to succeed but the data is lost. The tracking file would be missing entries, leading to incomplete `FilesTouched` data.\n\n**Recommendation:** Either check the `Close()` error explicitly, or use a pattern that flushes before returning:\n\n```go\ndefer func() {\n    if closeErr := f.Close(); closeErr != nil && err == nil {\n        err = fmt.Errorf(\"failed to close files touched tracking file: %w\", closeErr)\n    }\n}()\n```\n\n---\n\n## Issue 6: `handleLifecycleFileEdit` creates a new `StateStore` on every call instead of reusing\n\n**Location:** `/Users/alex/workspace/cli/.worktrees/3/cmd/entire/cli/lifecycle.go`, lines 200-208\n\n**Severity:** MEDIUM (architectural concern more than error handling)\n\n**Issue Description:** Every `FileEdit` event creates a new `session.NewStateStore(ctx)`, which calls `getGitCommonDir` (a `git rev-parse` subprocess). The `getGitCommonDir` result is cached per-CWD, so the subprocess only runs once. However, the `StateStore` struct is allocated fresh each time. For agents that make many file edits (e.g., a single turn editing 20+ files